WEBVTT

1
00:00:12.645 --> 00:00:14.996
Have you ever noticed when you ask someone to talk
你有没有注意到

2
00:00:13.740 --> 00:00:18.356
about a change they're making for the better in their personal lives,
当你向别人问及 他们为改善自己的生活所做的改变时

3
00:00:18.380 --> 00:00:20.340
they're often really energetic?
他们通常都是充满活力的？

4
00:00:20.835 --> 00:00:23.316
Whether it's training for a marathon,
不管这个改变是为马拉松准备

5
00:00:23.340 --> 00:00:24.596
picking up an old hobby,
还是重新拾起一份过去的爱好

6
00:00:24.620 --> 00:00:26.476
or learning a new skill,
再或者是学习一门新技能

7
00:00:26.500 --> 00:00:27.756
for most people,
对大多数来说

8
00:00:27.780 --> 00:00:33.020
self-transformation projects occupy a very positive emotional space.
自我改变通常包含着一个积极的情感方向

9
00:00:33.540 --> 00:00:35.996
Self-transformation is empowering,
自我改变是一个自我赋权的过程

10
00:00:36.020 --> 00:00:38.356
energizing, even exhilarating.
充满活力或者让人非常愉悦兴奋

11
00:00:38.380 --> 00:00:42.156
I mean just take a look at some of the titles of self-help books:
看看那些有关自我帮助的书籍的名字就知道了

12
00:00:42.180 --> 00:00:44.876
"Awaken the Giant Within,"
“叫醒内在的巨大力量”

13
00:00:44.900 --> 00:00:47.396
"Practicing the Power of Now,"
“掌控当下的力量”

14
00:00:47.420 --> 00:00:49.876
or here's a great one we can all relate to,
或者这里有一个典型的

15
00:00:49.900 --> 00:00:52.116
"You are a Badass:
“你不是个循规蹈矩的人”

16
00:00:52.140 --> 00:00:57.236
How to Stop Doubting Your Greatness and Start Living an Awesome Life."
“如何停止怀疑你的卓越指出以及开始一份精彩的生活”

17
00:00:57.260 --> 00:00:58.460
(Laughter)
（笑声）

18
00:00:59.860 --> 00:01:02.380
When it comes to self-transformation,
当事情和自我转变有关系的时候

19
00:01:03.060 --> 00:01:06.620
you can't help but get a sense of the excitement.
你所感受的兴奋感是无法控制的

20
00:01:08.660 --> 00:01:11.836
But there's another type of transformation
但是，也有另外一种类型的转变

21
00:01:11.860 --> 00:01:14.940
that occupies a very different emotional space.
这其中的情感倾向是非常不同的

22
00:01:15.900 --> 00:01:18.500
The transformation of organizations.
关于集体的转变

23
00:01:19.700 --> 00:01:21.036
If you're like most people,
就像和大多数的人反应一下

24
00:01:21.060 --> 00:01:25.436
when you hear the words "Our organization is going to start a transformation,"
当你听到“我们的组织”将会有一些变化的时候

25
00:01:25.460 --> 00:01:26.860
you're thinking, "Uh-oh."
你会想“不是吧”

26
00:01:27.246 --> 00:01:28.396
(Laughter)
（笑声）

27
00:01:28.420 --> 00:01:29.620
"Layoffs."
“要裁员啦”

28
00:01:30.620 --> 00:01:32.556
The blood drains from your face,
连你脸上的血液都沸腾了

29
00:01:32.580 --> 00:01:35.436
your mind goes into overdrive,
你的思维开始坐上了过山车

30
00:01:35.460 --> 00:01:38.700
frantically searching for some place to run and hide.
此刻最想做的时候就是逃离或者找地方躲起来

31
00:01:39.940 --> 00:01:41.436
Well, you can run,
当然，你可以跑掉

32
00:01:41.460 --> 00:01:42.740
but you really can't hide.
但是，你根本无处可藏

33
00:01:43.860 --> 00:01:46.836
Most of us spend the majority of our waking hours
我们中的大多数的大部分时间

34
00:01:46.860 --> 00:01:48.380
involved in organizations.
都是在集体中度过的

35
00:01:48.860 --> 00:01:51.956
And due to changes in globalization,
由于全球一体化带来的一些改变

36
00:01:51.980 --> 00:01:54.516
changes due to advances in technology
和科技进步所带来的转变

37
00:01:54.540 --> 00:01:56.356
and other factors,
以及其他的一些因素

38
00:01:56.380 --> 00:02:01.300
the reality is our organizations are constantly having to adapt.
事实的真相是，我们的组织必须连续不断的去适应

39
00:02:02.180 --> 00:02:03.396
In fact,
事实上

40
00:02:03.420 --> 00:02:07.300
I call this the era of "always-on" transformation.
我把这个叫做“改变永不停止的时代”

41
00:02:09.220 --> 00:02:11.476
When I shared this idea with my wife Nicola,
当我把这个想法和我太太Nicola分享的时候

42
00:02:11.500 --> 00:02:14.636
she said, "Always-on transformation?
她问到“永不停止的改变”？

43
00:02:14.660 --> 00:02:16.740
That sounds exhausting."
这听起来让人觉得很疲惫

44
00:02:17.460 --> 00:02:19.756
And that may be exactly what you're thinking --
这就和你想的一样

45
00:02:19.780 --> 00:02:21.356
and you would be right.
而且你可能是对的

46
00:02:21.380 --> 00:02:26.516
Particularly if we continue to approach the transformation of organizations
特别是，当我们持续向着组织改变方向靠近的时候

47
00:02:26.540 --> 00:02:27.900
the way we always have been.
也就是我们一直以来的样子

48
00:02:28.740 --> 00:02:31.156
But because we can't hide,
但是，因为我们无法躲藏

49
00:02:31.180 --> 00:02:32.876
we need to sort out two things.
我们需要弄清楚两件事情

50
00:02:32.900 --> 00:02:34.116
First,
第一

51
00:02:34.140 --> 00:02:36.876
why is transformation so exhausting?
为什么改变如此令人疲惫？

52
00:02:36.900 --> 00:02:38.660
And second, how do we fix it?
第二，我们应该怎么解决？

53
00:02:41.020 --> 00:02:42.236
First of all,
首先

54
00:02:42.260 --> 00:02:45.396
let's acknowledge that change is hard.
我们必须要承认，改变是困难的

55
00:02:45.420 --> 00:02:47.436
People naturally resist change,
人们自然而然的抗拒改变

56
00:02:47.460 --> 00:02:50.100
especially when it's imposed on them.
特别是这种改变是强加在他们身上的时候

57
00:02:51.020 --> 00:02:55.596
But there are things that organizations do that make change even harder
而且有一些组织把改变这件事情变得更难了更让人疲惫

58
00:02:55.620 --> 00:02:58.460
and more exhausting for people than it needs to be.
尽管改变本身并没那么糟糕

59
00:02:59.540 --> 00:03:00.756
First of all,
比如说

60
00:03:00.780 --> 00:03:04.220
leaders often wait too long to act.
领导们常常不会及时行动

61
00:03:04.860 --> 00:03:06.076
As a result,
后果是

62
00:03:06.100 --> 00:03:08.540
everything is happening in crisis mode.
所有的事情都在大家的危机情绪中发生了

63
00:03:10.140 --> 00:03:12.158
Which, of course, tends to be exhausting.
这种情绪当然会导致“精疲力尽”

64
00:03:13.180 --> 00:03:16.276
Or, given the urgency,
或者对于紧急情况来说

65
00:03:16.300 --> 00:03:20.220
what they'll do is they'll just focus on the short-term results,
他们会做的是基于短期内会有所结果的事情

66
00:03:21.140 --> 00:03:23.300
but that doesn't give any hope for the future.
这对未来并不会有什么好的改观

67
00:03:24.380 --> 00:03:28.100
Or they'll just take a superficial, one-off approach,
或者他们只会采取一些表面的，一次性的措施

68
00:03:28.860 --> 00:03:32.956
hoping that they can return back to business as usual
希望他们可以如同往常一样开展以往的工作

69
00:03:32.980 --> 00:03:35.580
as soon as the crisis is over.
当这种危机结束的时候

70
00:03:37.420 --> 00:03:38.636
This kind of approach
这种方式

71
00:03:38.660 --> 00:03:44.740
is kind of the way some students approach preparing for standardized tests.
就和学生为了标准考试准备的方式一样

72
00:03:46.100 --> 00:03:49.556
In order to get test scores to go up,
只是为了得到理想的分数

73
00:03:49.580 --> 00:03:52.180
teachers will end up teaching to the test.
老师们最终沦只为分数忙碌

74
00:03:52.980 --> 00:03:54.356
Now, that approach can work;
目前阶段，这种方式是有效的

75
00:03:54.380 --> 00:03:56.316
test results often do go up.
考试结果会变好

76
00:03:56.340 --> 00:04:00.116
But it fails the fundamental goal of education:
但是却失去了让学生能够在未来成功的

77
00:04:00.140 --> 00:04:04.260
to prepare students to succeed over the long term.
教育的本质职能

78
00:04:06.500 --> 00:04:09.020
So given these obstacles,
所以，面对这些困难的时候

79
00:04:09.980 --> 00:04:11.796
what can we do
我们能够做什么呢

80
00:04:11.820 --> 00:04:15.276
to transform the way we transform organizations
应该要改变改造组织的方式

81
00:04:15.300 --> 00:04:17.260
so rather than being exhausting,
而不是让人觉得精疲力尽

82
00:04:18.020 --> 00:04:20.860
it's actually empowering and energizing?
改变本身是让人有权利掌控感和经济充沛的吗？

83
00:04:21.980 --> 00:04:26.996
To do that, we need to focus on five strategic imperatives,
为了达到这样的目的，我们应该关注五个战略要点

84
00:04:27.020 --> 00:04:29.755
all of which have one thing in common:
这所有的要点都有一个相同的前提

85
00:04:29.779 --> 00:04:32.060
putting people first.
就是把人放在第一位

86
00:04:32.899 --> 00:04:35.556
The first imperative for putting people first
第一个以人为本的要点

87
00:04:35.580 --> 00:04:37.340
is to inspire through purpose.
是在目的中激励大家

88
00:04:37.940 --> 00:04:41.636
Most transformations have financial and operational goals.
大多数的改革都是有财务和管理目的的

89
00:04:41.660 --> 00:04:45.916
These are important and they can be energizing to leaders,
这些因素很重要，同时对领导来说是振奋人心的

90
00:04:45.940 --> 00:04:49.500
but they tend not to be very motivating to most people in the organization.
但对于组织中的其他大多数人来说，却不那么振奋人心

91
00:04:50.300 --> 00:04:52.076
To motivate more broadly,
为了更宽泛的激励大家

92
00:04:52.100 --> 00:04:56.500
the transformation needs to connect with a deeper sense of purpose.
这样的转变需要更好的和目标感结合

93
00:04:57.540 --> 00:04:58.740
Take LEGO.
拿乐高举个例子

94
00:04:59.460 --> 00:05:03.700
The LEGO Group has become an extraordinary global company.
乐高集团在有力的领导下已经是一个及其大的国际化集团

95
00:05:04.340 --> 00:05:06.076
Under their very capable leadership,
已经变成了非常大的国际化集团

96
00:05:06.100 --> 00:05:08.940
they've actually undergone a series of transformations.
事实上，他们也经历过一系列的改革

97
00:05:09.620 --> 00:05:12.836
While each of these has had a very specific focus,
他们所有的改革都有一个非常明确的目标

98
00:05:12.860 --> 00:05:14.156
the North Star,
比如说，具有连接和指导功能的

99
00:05:14.180 --> 00:05:15.996
linking and guiding all of them,
北星商场计划

100
00:05:16.020 --> 00:05:18.460
has been Lego's powerful purpose:
以及成为了乐高强有力的目的

101
00:05:19.300 --> 00:05:23.060
inspire and develop the builders of tomorrow.
那就是：启发和培养未来的主人翁们

102
00:05:24.180 --> 00:05:25.380
Expanding globally?
或者是为了企业的国际化的扩张？

103
00:05:25.980 --> 00:05:28.396
It's not about increasing sales,
这并不是为了增长销售额

104
00:05:28.420 --> 00:05:33.060
but about giving millions of additional children access to LEGO building bricks.
只是为了让成千上万的孩子可以享受乐高的乐趣

105
00:05:33.780 --> 00:05:35.180
Investment and innovation?
投资和动机？

106
00:05:35.780 --> 00:05:37.638
It's not about developing new products,
这也不是为了开发新产品

107
00:05:38.180 --> 00:05:40.476
but about enabling more children
这是为了促使孩子们

108
00:05:40.500 --> 00:05:44.020
to experience the joy of learning through play.
在游戏中找到学习的乐趣

109
00:05:45.260 --> 00:05:46.796
Not surprisingly,
这并不让人觉得惊讶

110
00:05:46.820 --> 00:05:51.900
that deep sense of purpose tends to be highly motivating to LEGO's people.
这种心底的目的认同感极大的激励了乐高的所有员工

111
00:05:53.940 --> 00:05:56.876
The second imperative for putting people first
以人为本的第二要点

112
00:05:56.900 --> 00:05:58.620
is to go all in.
就是全力以赴

113
00:05:59.900 --> 00:06:01.596
Too many transformations
对于大多数的改革来说

114
00:06:01.620 --> 00:06:05.356
are nothing more than head-count cutting exercises;
只是一场裁员运动

115
00:06:05.380 --> 00:06:08.860
layoffs under the guise of transformation.
用改革来掩饰裁员的目的

116
00:06:09.780 --> 00:06:11.836
In the face of relentless competition,
在激烈的竞争面前

117
00:06:11.860 --> 00:06:15.796
it may well be that you will have to take the painful decision
这可能是你需要作出的一个痛苦决定

118
00:06:15.820 --> 00:06:18.676
to downsize the organization,
减少组织的规模

119
00:06:18.700 --> 00:06:22.380
just as you may have to lose some weight in order to run a marathon.
就和你为了完成马拉松需要减轻一些体重一样

120
00:06:23.820 --> 00:06:25.036
But losing weight alone
但是只是减轻体重

121
00:06:25.060 --> 00:06:27.900
will not get you across the finish line with a winning time.
并不会让你成为马拉松的赢家

122
00:06:28.380 --> 00:06:29.580
To win
为了成为冠军

123
00:06:29.980 --> 00:06:31.460
you need to go all in.
你需要全力以赴

124
00:06:32.700 --> 00:06:35.740
You need to go all in.
重要的事情，再说一遍，全力以赴

125
00:06:36.980 --> 00:06:38.820
Rather than just cutting costs,
并不仅仅是减少成本

126
00:06:39.460 --> 00:06:41.996
you need to think about initiatives
你需要去思考那些在中期

127
00:06:42.020 --> 00:06:44.716
that will enable you to win in the medium term,
让你取胜的动机

128
00:06:44.740 --> 00:06:46.716
initiatives to drive growth,
那些会促使增长的动机

129
00:06:46.740 --> 00:06:50.796
actions that will fundamentally change the way the company operates,
那些可以从本质上改变公司运作的行动

130
00:06:50.820 --> 00:06:52.356
and very importantly,
还有非常重要的一点

131
00:06:52.380 --> 00:06:56.020
investments to develop the leadership and the talent.
‘加大投资去培养领导团队和那些有才华的人

132
00:06:58.500 --> 00:07:02.276
The third imperative for putting people first
以人为本的第三要点

133
00:07:02.300 --> 00:07:04.996
is to enable people with the capabilities
就是促使员工获得在改革过程中或者改革以后

134
00:07:05.020 --> 00:07:09.860
that they need to succeed during the transformation and beyond.
使他们成功的技能

135
00:07:12.100 --> 00:07:15.340
Over the years I've competed in a number of triathlons.
在这些年终，我所经历的铁人三项中

136
00:07:16.100 --> 00:07:18.276
You know, frankly, I'm not that good,
老实说，我并不是非常擅长

137
00:07:18.300 --> 00:07:22.316
but I do have one distinct capability;
但是我却是是有一项特别的能力

138
00:07:22.340 --> 00:07:26.020
I am remarkably fast at finding my bike.
我能非常迅速的找到我的自行车

139
00:07:26.460 --> 00:07:28.356
(Laughter)
（笑）

140
00:07:28.380 --> 00:07:30.196
By the time I finish the swim,
当我完成游泳的时候

141
00:07:30.220 --> 00:07:32.076
almost all the bikes are already gone.
几乎所有的自行车都不见了

142
00:07:32.100 --> 00:07:34.580
(Laughter)
（笑）

143
00:07:35.980 --> 00:07:40.036
Real triathletes know that each leg --
老资格铁人三项参赛者都知道所有的项目

144
00:07:40.060 --> 00:07:41.796
the swim, the bike, the run --
游泳、自行车、长跑

145
00:07:41.820 --> 00:07:44.316
really requires different capabilities,
所需要的技能其实是不一样的

146
00:07:44.340 --> 00:07:45.556
different tools,
不同的工具

147
00:07:45.580 --> 00:07:48.236
different skills, different techniques.
不同的技能以及不同的技巧

148
00:07:48.260 --> 00:07:50.716
Likewise when we transform organizations,
这和我们改造组织是一样的

149
00:07:50.740 --> 00:07:53.596
we need to be sure that we're giving our people
我们需要确定我们给我们的员工的技能和工具

150
00:07:53.620 --> 00:07:56.420
the skills and the tools they need along the way.
是他们在过程中所需要的

151
00:07:57.980 --> 00:07:59.196
Chronos,
Chronos,

152
00:07:59.220 --> 00:08:01.196
a global software company,
一个全球的软件生产商

153
00:08:01.220 --> 00:08:06.156
recognized the need to transfer from building products --
意识到他们需要把构建产品

154
00:08:06.180 --> 00:08:07.836
software products --
软件产品

155
00:08:07.860 --> 00:08:10.620
to building software as a service.
变成一种软件服务

156
00:08:11.620 --> 00:08:14.836
To enable its people to take that transformation,
为了促使他们的员工接受这样的改变

157
00:08:14.860 --> 00:08:17.556
first of all they invested in new tools
首先，他们对可以促使员工监控功能运用的

158
00:08:17.580 --> 00:08:22.636
that would enable their employees to monitor the usage of the features
新工具进行了投资

159
00:08:22.660 --> 00:08:25.420
as well as customer satisfaction with the new service.
同时也对客户对于新服务的满意度进行了关注

160
00:08:26.100 --> 00:08:29.796
They also invested in skill development,
他们也对员工技能提高进行了培训投入

161
00:08:29.820 --> 00:08:31.636
so that their employees would be able
所以他们的员工可以这个方面

162
00:08:31.660 --> 00:08:34.140
to resolve customer service problems on the spot.
也良好的解决了客户服务中的问题

163
00:08:34.780 --> 00:08:35.996
And very importantly,
还有非常重要的一点

164
00:08:36.020 --> 00:08:39.396
they also reinforced the collaborative behaviors that would be required
他们同时也加强了需要给客户提供

165
00:08:39.420 --> 00:08:43.460
to deliver an end-to-end seamless customer experience.
端到端无缝体验的的协作方式

166
00:08:44.499 --> 00:08:46.076
Because of these investments,
正是因为这些投资

167
00:08:46.100 --> 00:08:49.436
rather than feeling overwhelmed by the transformation,
而不是被改变本身搞得焦头烂额

168
00:08:49.460 --> 00:08:52.715
Chronos employees actually felt energized
Chronos的员工在他们的新岗位上

169
00:08:52.739 --> 00:08:54.820
and empowered in their new roles.
感到活力以及富有掌控感

170
00:08:56.020 --> 00:08:58.236
In the era of "always-on" transformation,
在一个改变永不下线的时代

171
00:08:58.260 --> 00:08:59.756
change is a constant.
变化是持续不断

172
00:08:59.780 --> 00:09:01.716
My fourth imperative therefore
第四个首要关注点

173
00:09:01.740 --> 00:09:05.540
is to instill a culture of continuous learning.
就是需要灌输一种长期学习的文化

174
00:09:06.620 --> 00:09:09.636
When Satya Nadella became the CEO of Microsoft
当Satya Nadella在2014年

175
00:09:09.660 --> 00:09:11.596
in February 2014,
当上微软的CEO的时候

176
00:09:11.620 --> 00:09:14.516
he embarked on an ambitious transformation journey
为了让这个企业在一个移动和云时代具有竞争力

177
00:09:14.540 --> 00:09:18.740
to prepare the company to compete in a mobile-first, cloud-first world.
他开启了一段富有野心的改变旅程

178
00:09:19.460 --> 00:09:21.756
This included changes to strategy,
这包括战略上的改变

179
00:09:21.780 --> 00:09:22.996
the organization
对于公司来说

180
00:09:23.020 --> 00:09:24.700
and very importantly, the culture.
非常重要的，文化

181
00:09:26.100 --> 00:09:30.420
Microsoft's culture at the time was one of silos and internal competition --
微软当时主要是简仓文化（一种企业架构文化）和内部竞争

182
00:09:31.140 --> 00:09:33.340
not exactly conducive to learning.
这对于学习文化的构建并没有帮助

183
00:09:34.300 --> 00:09:36.140
Nadella took this head-on.
Nadella采取了正面直上的方式

184
00:09:37.380 --> 00:09:40.796
He rallied his leadership around his vision
为了形成有活力的学习文化

185
00:09:40.820 --> 00:09:43.340
for a living, learning culture,
他根据自己的想法，整合了自己的领导方式

186
00:09:44.060 --> 00:09:46.396
shifting from a fixed mindset,
从固定思维转变也就是说

187
00:09:46.420 --> 00:09:49.796
where your role was to show up as the smartest person in the room,
你要做团体里面最聪明的人

188
00:09:49.820 --> 00:09:51.636
to a growth mindset,
想要培养一个不断进步的心态

189
00:09:51.660 --> 00:09:57.140
where your role was to listen, to learn and to bring out the best in people.
你需要倾听别人、学习和激发人们最好的一面

190
00:09:58.540 --> 00:09:59.796
Well, early days,
早些日子

191
00:09:59.820 --> 00:10:02.940
Microsoft employees already noticed this shift in the culture --
微软的员工们已经意识到文化中的这种转变

192
00:10:03.900 --> 00:10:07.300
clear evidence of Microsoft putting people first.
也就是微软把人放在第一位

193
00:10:08.380 --> 00:10:11.940
My fifth and final imperative is specifically for leaders.
我的第五个也就是最后一个首要观点是特别针对领导者的

194
00:10:13.020 --> 00:10:14.676
In a transformation,
在转变的过程中

195
00:10:14.700 --> 00:10:16.260
a leader needs to have a vision,
一个领导者需要有一个方向

196
00:10:16.980 --> 00:10:19.620
a clear road map with milestones,
一个有明确目标的计划

197
00:10:20.420 --> 00:10:24.876
and then you need to hold people accountable for results.
然后你需要让人们为结果负责

198
00:10:24.900 --> 00:10:26.853
In other words, you need to be directive.
换而言之，就是你需要为他们指出方向

199
00:10:28.060 --> 00:10:31.196
But in order to capture the hearts and minds of people,
为了洞察大家的心态和想法

200
00:10:31.220 --> 00:10:33.620
you also need to be inclusive.
你还需要具有包容能力

201
00:10:34.500 --> 00:10:38.260
Inclusive leadership is critical to putting people first.
包容性的领导方式就是严格的把人放在第一位

202
00:10:39.740 --> 00:10:41.540
I live in the San Francisco Bay area.
我住在三番海湾区域

203
00:10:42.500 --> 00:10:43.716
And right now,
现在

204
00:10:43.740 --> 00:10:46.220
our basketball team is the best in the league.
我们的篮球队是联盟里面的第一名

205
00:10:46.780 --> 00:10:49.436
We won the 2015 championship,
我们在2015年拿到了冠军

206
00:10:49.460 --> 00:10:51.700
and we're favored to win again this year.
而且我们也很可能拿下今年的冠军

207
00:10:52.420 --> 00:10:54.476
There are many explanations for this.
为此，他们做了很多准备

208
00:10:54.500 --> 00:10:56.220
They have some fabulous players,
他们召集了一些很有实力的球员

209
00:10:56.940 --> 00:10:58.716
but one of the key reasons
但是最关键的一原因之一

210
00:10:58.740 --> 00:11:04.180
is their head coach, Steve Kerr, is an inclusive leader.
是因为他们的教练Steve Kerr 是个具有包容性的领导

211
00:11:05.180 --> 00:11:07.796
When Kerr came to the Warriors in 2014,
当Kerr2014年来勇士执教的时候

212
00:11:07.820 --> 00:11:10.500
the Warriors were looking for a major transformation.
勇士正在寻求改变

213
00:11:11.300 --> 00:11:15.780
They hadn't won a national championship since 1975.
1975年之后他们就再也没有赢得过冠军

214
00:11:17.460 --> 00:11:20.636
Kerr came in, and he had a clear vision,
Kerr来了之后，他有一个清晰的想法

215
00:11:20.660 --> 00:11:23.060
and he immediately got to work.
并且，他立马投入了工作

216
00:11:24.300 --> 00:11:25.636
From the outset,
从一开始

217
00:11:25.660 --> 00:11:29.756
he reached out and engaged the players and the staff.
他就让工作人员和球员一起工作

218
00:11:29.780 --> 00:11:34.060
He created an environment of open debate and solicited suggestions.
他创造了一个可以公开辩论和寻求建议的环境

219
00:11:35.180 --> 00:11:36.876
During games he would often ask,
在比赛期间，他会问一些问题

220
00:11:36.900 --> 00:11:38.780
"What are you seeing that I'm missing?"
比如，“你看到了什么是我错过的？”

221
00:11:39.820 --> 00:11:45.580
One the best examples of this came in game four of the 2015 finals.
最好的一个例子是，2015决赛第四轮的时候

222
00:11:46.420 --> 00:11:48.540
The Warriors were down two games to one
勇士二比一落后

223
00:11:49.700 --> 00:11:53.860
when Kerr made the decision to change the starting lineup;
Kerr决定换掉初始阵容

224
00:11:54.420 --> 00:11:57.820
a bold move by any measure.
不管从哪个角度来说，都是一个非常大胆的举动

225
00:11:59.180 --> 00:12:02.100
The Warriors won the game and went on to win the championship.
勇士赢了那场比赛并且在之后拿了赛季冠军

226
00:12:02.780 --> 00:12:04.036
And it is widely viewed
这个决定被广泛评价为

227
00:12:04.060 --> 00:12:07.740
